FACTORIAL PROGRAM

The GNU C++ compiler comes bundled with the NIH (National Institute
of Health) class library, and this library contains code for the class
Integer.  Variables of type Integer can take very large values.  If you
have access to a GNU C++ system, you can try the factorial program that
we have written here.

Here is some example output:

100! =

   9332621544394415268169923885626670049071596826438162146859296389521759
   9993229915608941463976156518286253697920827223758251185210916864000000
   000000000000000000

Observe that 100! ends with 24 zeros.  It is easy to check that this is
correct.  Further checks on the accuracy of this number are not so easy.

In the file prn.c you will see that we have inserted a newline character
after every 70 digits.  If we did not do this, then we would have very
long lines.

Observe that the factorial() function that we wrote in fact.c is very
elementary and natural.  All the hard coding work has been encapsulated
in the NIH class library.  Thus the programmer who uses the library only
has to write code that deals with objects, in our case Integers.

---
In the future, the Standard Template Library will provide many standard
classes, including a large integer class.  Eventually, we expect all C++
compilers to incorporate this standard.  Then, a program such as this
one will not be tied to a specific C++ system.
